<P>I writ to you a very hasty Letter&punc; being warm'd in the Cause of an old ac|quaintance, in which I was sure you would cenc$r, I mean John Dennis, whose Circumstances were describ'd to me in the most moving Manner. I went next day with the Lord to whom you directed your Letter and play, which at my re|turn home, I receiv'd but yesterday. I thank you for your agreeable present to my Grotto, for your more agreeable Letter, and your most excellent Tran&s;lation of Voltaire, to whom you have preserv'd all the Beauty he had, and added the Nerves he wanted. This &s;hort acknowledgment is all I can make just now; I am just taken up by M^r. Thomson, in the perusal of a n$w Poem he has brought me: I wish you were with us. The first day I see London, I will wait on you, on ma|ny Accounts, but on none more than my being affectionately, and with true Esteem, dear Sir,</P>
