<DATELINE><DATE>July 21, 1738</DATE></DATELINE></OPENER>
<P>I need not a&s;sure you in many Words, that I join my Suffrage in$irely with Lord B's in general, after a fourth a a$ling of your Tragedy of Cesar. I think no Characters were are more nobly &s;ustained than those of Cesar and Brutu$ in par|ticular: You $xc$l throughted in the p$$tne&s;s of Sentiment, and $word$ that I never met with more &s;triking Sentences, or lively short Reprizes. There is almost every where such a Dignity in the Scenes, that instead of painting and any one Scene, $word$ s$rra point out any that $word$ it, any degree $erc$pt you would a little wise that of the $word$ in the last $ct). That Dignity is admirably $word$ with Softne&s;s, in the Scenes between Cesar and Ca$pharnia: And all these be|tween Cesar and Brutus are a $obi Strife between Greatne&s;s and Humanity. The management of the whole is as artful as it is noble. Whatever particular Remarks we have made further, will be rather the Subject of Conversation than a Letter of which we &s;hall both be glad of an Opportunity, either here at Trickenham, or in Town, as &s;hall best suit your Conveniency. Pray, Sir, let this confirm you in the Opinion you kindly, and indeed justly, entertain of the Wish I feel (and ever fel$, notwithstanding Mistakes) to be and to be thought,</P>
