<OPENER><DATELINE><DATE>Sept. 12. 1738.</DATE></DATELINE>
<SALUTE>Sir,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>I have now little to say of your Tragedy, which I return with my Thanks for your Indulgence to my Opinion, which $word$ $o a$$$lutely de&s;er'd to, that I wish I had $ro&s;o'd le&s;s, frequently. I cannot, find another thing I think a fault in you. But my $ord thinks, three things may yet reconsider'd. Brutus, $n Sight of the $arran$ &s;ign'd for his Death, takes at once the Resolution of murdering Ce|sar, as none of his Father. Que$e, Whether in the $$ene that follows between him and Cesar, all $$nderne&s;s on the &s;ide of Brutus, and all beyond the point of Honour that Friend&s;hip exacted, &s;hould not rather be avoided than heigh|$$ned?</P>
<P>Another Quere is, Whether it would not bege$ more Indignation in the Au|dience against Ca&s;sius and more Compa&s;sion, for Cesar, to $he$ that Ca&s;sius suspected Brutus to be Cesars Sen, and therefore $$acted from Brutus the $ath of $$aring neither Father, Relation, &amp;c.</P>
<P>The third thing is, Whether the Efforts made by Cesar to pre$ent the Civil War, not only by the equall Offer he made, while the matter was under Deba$$ in the &s;enate (and which the Consuls Lentulus and Marcellus refused to report to the Senate), but by the Me&s;sage he sent to Pempcy, when he was at Branda&s;ion, to desire a Meeting, to settle the Matter, and avoid the Civil War.&mdash;$id. $word$ $on$m. d$. bell. Civili, lib. I. The mention of these &s;omewhere in the Hay might help to $word$ the Prepo&s;se&s;sion against Cesar.</P>
<P>After our little Cavils (for so we will rather call $word$ and verbal Points of Cri+&s;icism) we owe you the Justice to $word$ highly, what we highly approve, and you need not desire us to &s;peak as we think: 'Tis what we have (in different Ways) done all our Lives, where it was to our prejudice, and cannot but do here, where it is to our Honour. I only wish you a Stage, Actors, and an Audi|ence worthy of you, and it.&mdash;I have often wished to live to see the Day when Prologues and Epilogues &s;hould be no more. I wish a great Genius would break thro' the $illy, usele&s;s, Formality. But at least I would have one try, to leave the Audience full of the Effects of a good Tragedy, without an Epilogue. $et
<PB N="390" REF="412" MS="Y">
me add another Hint, concerning the apparatus and Circumstantials of your Play (since I have nothing left more to wish in the Play itself); that you would intitle i$ barely. The Tragedy of Cesar, and give no Intimation of his being a Patrie$; for I fear, instead of preparing the Audience, it might revolt them, and put all the little Criticks upon carping previously $word$ the very design and Cha|racter; which would appear by and with the proper Preparations, in the Piece on the Stage. Another thing was a Thought of my Lord's, that i$ &s;hould be printed before Acting, a day or two; for the Sentiments are so thick $own, and the Sense so deep sometimes, that they require more attention and Thought than the Hearer may be apt to give on the first Representation. I am not positive&punc; either as to this, or my Thought, but &s;ubmit them to your Consideration.</P>
<P>I have nothing to add, but to lament $ur unhappine&s;s, that we cannot see you personally to conform what these Letters tell you, of our real Opinion of your Work, Esteem of its Author, and wishes for your Succe&s;s, in this, and every thing.</P>
